<TITLE> New rules would help Wall Street: Obama adviser </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, Mon Aug 11, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Barack Obama sees an overhaul of Wall Street regulations as important to restoring trust in U.S. markets and could move early on it if he wins the White House, according to a senior adviser to the candidate. Some in the industry warn that too strict a regulatory structure would stifle innovation. But Austan Goolsbee, a top economic adviser to Democratic White House hopeful Obama, told Reuters in an interview a sensible plan would lead U.S. markets to function more smoothly. "It ought to strike fear in the heart of every market-favoring person that you've got major things undermining the public trust in our capital markets," Goolsbee said. Asked how quickly Obama would be ready to push an overhaul, he said, "It could be early.
